{"key":"processedPost-15317027","value":{"id":15317027,"first":15315434,"last":15319607,"when":1320335856,"utime":"11/03/11 06:57 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />It's like if the top dont want to colonize <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/stars.gif\" alt=\":stars:\" title=\":stars:\"/><br /></blockquote><br /><br />This is very common with excessively large substrates.&nbsp; In the future, I'd stick with substrates 2\" in depth, which will give a far higher biological efficiency than thicker ones, colonize and fruit faster, and be much less susceptible to oxygen starvation(anaerobic) in the core.<br /><br />In wild conditions, cubensis tends to fruit from the edges of the cow manure, rather than right out the top.&nbsp; Growers often forget this fact of nature when we try to manipulate conditions to our own liking rather than to the liking of the mycelium.&nbsp; I've never been in favor of deep substrates, other than for straw, which by its very nature has lots of air pockets within the substrate.<br />RR","title":"Re: Help: Causes of tubs stalling ?"}}